Let $\mathcal{L}$ be the language consisting of a binary symbol $+$ and a unary relation $<$ (less than), and let $\mathrm{Th}(\mathcal{L})$ be the theory in this language consisting of the following axioms:
\begin{align*}
&\forall x \forall y \forall z ((x+y)+z = x + (y+z)) \tag{associativity of +}\\
&\forall x \forall y (x+y = y+x) \tag{commutativity of +}\\
&\forall x (x+0 = x) \tag{identity element of +}\\
&\forall x \forall y \exists z (x+z = y) \tag{existence of additive inverses}\\
&\forall x \forall y \forall z ((x<y \land y<z) \rightarrow x<z) \tag{transitivity of $<$}\\
&\forall x \forall y (x<y \rightarrow \exists z ((x<z \land z<y) \land \neg\exists w ((x<w \land w<y) \land w\neq z))) \tag{dense linear order}
\end{align*}

Given the formula $\psi(x)\equiv \exists y (x+y+1=0)$, determine whether $\mathrm{Th}(\mathcal{L})\vdash \forall x \psi(x)$ or not.
